AU  - Villagra, S.
AU  - Giraudo, C.
TI  - Systemic aspects of sheep production in the province of Rio Negro.
T2  - Revista Argentina de Produccion Animal
M3  - Journal article
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - Sheep production in Rio Negro province, Argentina is very important for 60% of its population. The relief, climate and vegetation characteristics all affect the production systems. Two different regions for sheep production are characterized as Western Extra Andean Patagonia and Monte Austral. Both regions have smallholders with little infrastructure and low use of technology. Wool production is the main source of income derived from these systems. The low survival rate of lambs limits meat production, flock size and the impact of any breeding programme. In the Western Extra Andean Patagonia, it is possible to increase production rates by controlling sheep nutrition before delivery, protecting lambs from predators and from extreme cold during the first hours after birth. This requires that meadows are excluded from grazing for nine months and grazed for three months (one month before delivery up to two months after delivery). This proposed management practice requires a relatively low investment for fencing the meadows. Due to lack of surface water and meadows, grazing is conditioned by the location of watering points in Monte Austral Rionegrino. Drought proved to be the cause of significant mortalities in farms with a poor water distribution because of the uneven distribution of grazing, leaving sub-utilized versus overgrazed areas. Most small landholders cannot afford the investment necessary for increasing the amount of watering points in order to change the distribution of grazing under the current credit conditions. It is concluded that in Western Extra Andean Patagonia, low investment and simple management practices can bring about significant positive changes in production. However, in Monte Austral region, water distribution should be improved by making available new alternative credit for farmers. Technical assistance is needed for the implementation of the proposed management in both regions.
