TI  - Irrigation management and splitting of nitrogen application as affected on grain yield and water productivity of hybrid and inbred rice.
T2  - 8th African Crop Science Society Conference, El-Minia, Egypt, 27-31 October 2007
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - The studies were carried out at the Experimental Farm of Rice Research and Training Center (RRTC), Sakha, Kafr El-Sheikh, Egypt, during 2002 and 2003 rice seasons, to study the productivity of two Egyptian rice cultivars namely, SK 2025H (hybrid) and Sakha 104 (inbred) as affected by four irrigation regimes namely, continuous flooding, continuous saturation, irrigation every 6 and 8 days and six time of nitrogen application namely, (N1) all nitrogen dose applied as basal and incorporated into the dry soil, (N2) 2/3 basal+1/3 at panicle initiation (PI), (N3) three equal doses as basal+mid tillering (MT)+PI, (N4) 1/2 basal+1/2 at PI, (N5) 1/2 basal+1/4 at MT+1/4 at PI and (N6) four equal doses, as basal+MT+PI+flowering. The experiments were laid out in a split-split plot design, with four replications. The irrigation regimes were in the main plots, cultivars were in the sub-plots. However, the tie of nitrogen application occupied the sub-sub plots. The main results showed that, most of growth attributes, grain yield and its components were significantly decreased as increasing irrigation intervals up to 8 days, with no significant differences among the first three irrigation treatments in grain yield in 2002 season and between continuous saturation and flooding in 2003 season. Continuous flooding consumed the highest amount of irrigation water. Furthermore, continuous saturation recorded the highest water productivity (0.82 and 0.85 kg/m3) and minimum yield reduction (2.54 and 1.99%) with water saved about (21.2%) compared to continuous flooding treatment for Sakha 104 and SK 2025H, respectively. SK 2025H hybrid rice significantly surpassed Sakha 104 for growth (chlorophyll content, dry matter production, LAI), grain yield and its components (number of panicles/m2, number of filled grains/panicle and panicle weight) except the 1000-grain weight. Splitting of nitrogen application was superior to single dose application. The highest grain yield of 10.43 t/ha was recorded with N3in 2002 season and it was 10.01 t/ha with N6in 2003 season. However, N1recorded the lowest values of grain yield and its components as well as the highest unfilled grain percentage. Generally, kept the soil at saturation condition with SK 2025H hybrid rice and splitting nitrogen application gave similar grain yield as the yield of continuous flooding for both hybrid and inbred rice with only 2-3% reduction in grain yield with increases water productivity up to a maximum value. As well as almost 20-22% of irrigation water can be saved if all farmers followed this practice.
