TY  - JOUR
AU  - Wang, Ru-lin
AU  - Zou, Yu-jia
AU  - Dong, Shu-heng
AU  - Li, Jin-jian
AU  - Dong, Xiao-bin
AU  - Zhang, Yu-fang
TI  - The relationship between snow disasters and the human well-being of farmers and herders in the Dadu River Basin.
T2  - Ecological Informatics
M3  - Journal article
AB  - In the context of global warming, various regions have witnessed frequent meteorological disasters, and human lives are increasingly affected by these disasters. Snow disasters are among the most severe natural disasters affecting the development of agriculture and animal husbandry in the Dadu River Basin (DRB). Therefore, it is necessary to investigate the spatiotemporal variation patterns of snow disasters and comprehensively assess their risk. Based on meteorological data from 2000 to 2019, this study analyzed the spatial distribution and temporal variations in snow disaster frequency, duration, depth, and level in the DRB. We constructed an evaluation index system for the human well-being (HWB) of farmers and herders in the DRB and quantitatively analyzed the relationship between HWB and snow disasters. Furthermore, the key factors affecting the responses of farmers and herders to snow disasters were identified. The results show that the spatial distribution characteristics of snow disaster frequency, duration, mean snow depth, and snow disaster level in the DRB were relatively similar, with high values in the north and low values in the south. The northern high-value center is located in the Aba-Maerkang-Hongyuan region in the northeastern upper reaches. This region experiences the most frequent and severe snow disasters in the DRB. There were apparent interdecadal fluctuations in the frequency and duration of snow disasters, average snow depth, and snow disaster levels. Moreover, comprehensive risk zoning for snow disasters in the DRB was conducted using Geographic Information System technology. The results showed that high-risk areas were mainly distributed in the Aba-northwestern Hongyuan region of the northeastern DRB. The sub-high-risk areas were located at the periphery of the high-risk areas, including eastern Rangtang, northern Maerkang, and eastern Hongyuan. The medium-risk areas included central Rangtang and central Maerkang. In addition, Maerkang in the upper reaches of the DRB, Kangding in the middle reaches, and Shimian in the lower reaches had high HWB levels for farmers and herders during 2000-2019, exhibiting distinct administrative center characteristics. Regarding temporal variation, the HWB level in the entire DRB gradually increased. Five typical regions, namely Aba, Maerkang, Rangtang, Luding, and Danba, have been selected to explore the possible impacts of snow disasters on the HWB of farmers and herders since the 21st century. For every 1% increase in snow disaster risk, the HWB indices of farmers and herders decreased by 0.513, 0.485, 0.321, 0.064, and 0.267%. Snow disasters affect the HWB of farmers and herders primarily through direct or indirect impacts on agricultural productivity (per capita arable land area and per capita grassland area), overall labor capacity (rural population and the number of agricultural, forestry, animal husbandry, and fishery workers), per capita meat production at the end of the year, per capita value-added of the primary industry, per capita net income of farmers and herders, and urbanization rate.
