TI  - Programmed fertilizer nitrogen application strategies for optimising maize grain yields on sandy soils, Kasungu plain, central Malawi.
T2  - Malawi Journal of Agricultural Sciences
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Three field experiments were conducted at Lisasadzi and Mwimba in Kasungu during the 1988/89 cropping season to investigate fertilizer N management options under rain-fed conditions on sandy ferallitic latosols of the Kasungu and Kamphuru series. The recommended fertilizer N management strategy of applying N in two split applications as a basal and a top dressing, was compared with a programmed fertilizers N application strategy that supplied N in small quantities designed to meet the crop's demand only. The currently recommended rate of 90 kg N ha-1that is applied in two split applications was also subjected to single and multiple N split applications, designed to mimic smallholder practices of applying fertilizer N late and/or in single dose applications. Fertilizer N significantly increased maize grain yields at both sites, further confirming that N is still the most deficient nutrient element in these soils. Optimum maize grain yields were realized with fertilizer N rates above the nationally recommended rate of 90 kg N ha-1, whereas maximum grain yields were achieved with an application of 180 kg N ha-4when applied in six split applications. Thus, fertilizer N use-efficiency was maximized with a programmed fertilizer nitrogen application strategy that supplied N in small quantities that meets the crop's demand only and minimized losses. This essentially amounts to "feeding" the maize crop with N based on the N demand function and the stage of crop growth. Split fertilizer N applications, for the recommended rate of 90 kg N ha-1applied within six weeks after crop emergence were significantly better than single dose applications applied during the same period. This finding gives further credence to the strategy of applying N to the maize crop based on the crop's N demand function. A single dose applied six weeks after crop emergence performed better than a single dose applied at crop emergence. This is an unexpected finding that can be attributed to continuous and heavy rainfall during the 1988/89 cropping season, compared with the 1987/88 cropping season, which most likely leached fertilizers N beyond the crop root zone in these coarse-textured feralitic latosols characterized by low soil-water and nutrient holding capacities. From these results, it can be concluded that for coarse-textured latosols, relativity higher rates of N than presently recommended should be applied to optimize maize grain yields. To maximize maize grain yields, more than the two split fertilizer N applications are required. This is most especially applicable to farmers endowed with some resources and managing relatively smaller plts of land. Depending on the rainfall pattern, some benefits may accrue form delayed N applications during years of high rainfall, whereas during years of average or below average rainfall, all the N may be applied in one single dose application early in the season with no significant loss in maize grain yields.
