TY  - JOUR
AU  - Liu, Jhih-Yun
AU  - Chang, Hung-Hao
TI  - Factors associated with the choice of farm households to adopt a protected cultivation structure: empirical analysis using agricultural census data of Taiwan.
T2  - Journal of the Agricultural Association of Taiwan
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Owing to the intensification of climate change, the loss in agricultural income resulting from natural disasters has reached an historical high. Under the pressure to conform with trade liberalization, low-cost imported agricultural products to Taiwan have influenced the Taiwanese agricultural product market. To improve farm household wellbeing and to assist the domestic agricultural market, in recent years the Taiwanese agricultural authority has begun to promote the use of a protected cultivation structure and provided subsidies for constructing facilities. However, the current adoption rates of protected cultivation structures are low. Previous studies do not analyze the factors associated with the choices of farm households to adopt a protected cultivation structure. This paper fulfills the knowledge gap of previous studies by providing information on the current use of the protected cultivation structure in Taiwan. This study used the 2015 agricultural census survey in Taiwan. We limited our sample to farms that produced vegetables, fruits, flowers and mushrooms. In the empirical analysis, we first analyzed the factors associated with the choice of the farm to adopt a protected cultivation structure by applying the Bivariate Probit Model. We then differentiated protected cultivation structures into simple and strong types. We also analyzed the determinants of farm households to choose different types of protected cultivation structures using the Multinomial Logit Model. The results showed the area of land has a significant and positive impact on the probability of farmers using agricultural cultivation facilities. Younger farm operators have a higher probability of using agricultural cultivation structures. This study also found that compared to vegetable farmhouse, farmhouses that mainly engaged in flower and mushroom have a significantly increased chance of using protected cultivation structures or selecting simple or strong ones. Based on our empirical results, we suggest subsidies for agricultural cultivation facilities consider the types of cultivated crops and the age of the head of the farm households. In so doing, the policy goal of improving farm household income and wellbeing can be achieved in a more effective way.
