AU  - Johnsen, F. H.
AU  - Mwaseba, D. L.
AU  - Mombo, F. M.
TI  - Farmer perspectives on the usefulness of technologies introduced by on-farm research: the case of the TARP II - SUA programme.
T2  - Noragric Report
M3  - Bulletin
AB  - The research programme 'Food Security and Household Income for Smallholder Farmers: Applied Research with Emphasis on Women' (TARPII-SUA) was carried out from September 2000 to June 2005 in Tanzania. TARPII-SUA included 34 research projects, of which 32 introduced technologies on-farm. The present study examines to what extent farmers still use the technologies that were introduced during the TARPII-SUA program and identifies the farmers' reasons for adopting or rejecting the technologies. Ten projects were selected for fieldwork: commercialization of cassava root (project 010); rainwater harvesting (project 012); chicken diseases (project 015); management of witch weed (Strigaspp.) (project 018); sweet potato germplasm maintenance and evaluation (project 021); milk collection, processing and marketing (project 027); farmer organizations (project 028); ticks and tick-born diseases (project 030); sequential cropping systems (project 032); and common bean varieties (project 043). The study was conducted in 20 villages in the Eastern Zone and Southern Highlands Zone that were project sites under TARPII-SUA. The main reasons that farmers give for adoption of introduced technologies are substantial improvements of income and food security, as expected in the project objectives. The reasons for rejecting technologies are much more diverse and include failure of the technologies to produce tangible benefits under unfavourable weather conditions (drought), technologies not being accessible to farmers, technologies not matching the farmers' priorities, introduced varieties not having the attributes that farmers prefer, expectations not being fulfilled, required inputs being too expensive, outputs not being marketable at attractive prices, and too high workload associated with the technologies. Based on the farmers' assessments, some success factors for on-farm research are suggested. Suggestions are also made for further research on the TARPII-SUA projects.
