TI  - Hatchery management in Bangladesh.
T2  - Aquaculture Asia Magazine
M3  - Journal article
AB  - A survey was conducted to collect information on fish hatchery management practices by interviewing 21 hatchery owners in Bangladesh [date not given]. It was shown that The establishment year of the surveyed hatcheries ranged from 1981 to 1985. The maximum hatcheries were established during 1986-1991. The hatchery was the livelihood of 9 owners, while 12 owners had other businesses. Only 9.52% of owners had graduation level education. 14.29% of owners had no training, while 19.05% had received short term training from the District Fisheries Office. 55% owners received training from other owners/farm managers and the rest gained knowledge from the Upazilla Fisheries Office. About 47.62% of owners had funds for seed production from their own sources. About 33.33 and 14.29% of owners got their funds as a loan from relatives and friends and from banks, respectively. Only 4.76% hatchery owners got their loan from NGOs. Hatchery owners had no transportation facilities of their own. About 52.38% owners mentioned the communication facilities as excellent, while 37.08 and 9.52% owners mentioned the facility as good and not good, respectively. None of the hatcheries had specialists but employed skilled and unskilled labourers. The maximum area of the surveyed hatcheries 24.75 decimals and minimum was 5.78 decimal, with an average of 11.125.19 decimals. The hatcheries had only stocking ponds for broodstock management and did not rear fry. The maximum number of stocking ponds was six and the minimum was 2 (41.05 average). About 80.95 and 19.05% of owners claimed that water quality was satisfactory and moderately satisfactory, respectively. 90 and 9.52% stated that soil quality was satisfactory and moderately satisfactory, respectively. 95.24% owners reported that there were no disease problems in their farms. 61.90% owners reported that the land use for hatchery purposes was their own, while 38.10% reported having both leased and owned land. The use of feed for brood fish was comparatively common. Both inorganic and organic fertilizers were used to increase pond vegetation and productivity. About 28.57 and 9.52% owners claimed that production of hatcheries was limited due to lack of technical knowledge insufficient water in the dry season, respectively. The lack of credit marketing system were crucial constraints. Theft of fish and toll collection by terrorists were the main constraints related to leasing. 23.81% of hatchery owners experienced flooding problems. The policy and recommendations for hatchery management are given.
