TI  - Effects of acute high temperature stress on heat tolerance, tissue structure and antioxidant system of adult Eriocheir sinensisin winter.
T2  - Marine Fisheries
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Eriocheir sinensisis sensitive to the change of water temperature. The body temperature of E. sinensischanges with the water environment. Every winter adult E. sinensisfrom the Yangtze River need to migrate to the Yangtze River Estuary for mating and breeding and the appropriate water temperature is 8-11°C. However, the water temperature of the Yangtze River Estuary is generally rising, which will have a potential impact on the physiological metabolism and body homeostasis of aquatic animals. This study took adult E. sinensisin winter as the research object and took temperature as a single factor variable. The critical temperature method and lethal temperature method were used to determine the heat tolerance level of E. sinensis. The tissue structure changes of gills and hepatopancreas under different water temperatures (10°C, 15°C, 20°C, 25°C, 30°C, 32°C,) were analyzed, and the activities of antioxidant enzymes (superoxide dismutase. SOD: catalase. CAT; glutathione, GSH; glutathione peroxidase, GSH-Px; glutathione S-transferase, GST) and the content of malondialdehyde (MDA) in hepatopancreas were measured. The results of critical temperature method showed that the critical thermal maximum (CTM) of E. sinensisincreased with the decrease of the heating rates. The thermal tolerance of E. sinensiswas better at low heating rates of 1-2°C . h-1. The lethal temperature method showed that the 24 h upper incipient semi-lethal temperature was 31.26°C at the basic water temperature of 10°C. Moreover the results of tissue structure and antioxidant system under acute high temperature stress showed that the damage degree of tissue structure in E. sinensisincreased gradually with the increase of high temperature stress. Under acute high temperature stress at 15°C- 25°C, cellular and tissue abnormalities appeared in the gill filaments and part of hepatopancreas and the activity of antioxidant enzymes significantly increased. In 30°C-32°C group. pathological changes appeared in the tissues of E. sinensis, the activity of antioxidant enzymes decreased significantly (P< 0.05), and the content of MDA increased sharply. The study can provide a reference for the analysis of environmental suitability in winter adult E. sinensisfarming.
