TI  - Household water security and related factors in Mbeya Region, Tansania.
T2  - Proceedings, International Conference on Interdisciplinary Research and Development (ICIRD), 29-31 October 2015, Maejo University, Chiang Mai, Thailand
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - Water security is essential for people survival, wellbeing and economic development. Knowing water security and its associated factors could help relevant sectors to develop appropriate measures to improve water security. The study aimed to identify the household water security status and determine factors related to household water security level in Mbeya Region. This Cross sectional study used a sample size estimation formula for multiple logistic regression to calculate for samples. Stratified randomly sampling was applied to select 358 samples to response to a structured questionnaire interview. The questionnaire was constructed based on the research questions and literature reviewed. The questionnaire was reviewed by 3 experts for content validity and had 0.77 Cronbach's alpha coefficient, an acceptable reliability. Data were entered into MS excel and statistical analysis was done using stata software program. Descriptive statistics were used to identify the status of household's water security. Bivariate analysis was used to determine the relationship between each dependent variable and the household water security, whereas the multiple logistic regression was applied to determine the association among socio-demographic, knowledge, policies and attitude on water security, presented odd ratio (OR), adjusted OR with 95% of CI and p-value. The study revealed that from the total of 358 households, 76.54% households had inadequate water security. Almost half of majority of households 44.13%, accessed public water tap/stand pipe for domestic purposes, 47.77%, accessed rainfall collection for agriculture purposes and 27.65% accessed river sources for livestock purposes. The majority of households spent less than or 30 minutes for fetching water with the average of 46.56 minutes during dry seasons and 27.01 minutes during wet season. Almost the households accessed water within less than or equal to 400 m from the water sources and average distance were 343.75 m during wet season and 706.09 m during dry season. The average daily domestic water use in households was 109.43 liter per households per day and 21.89 liter per person per day. Water used for agriculture was 54.64 liter per day and 130.30 liter per household per day for livestock. Household's water usage indicated absolute water scarcity less than 500 m3per capita/year indicator index for economic activities. Socio-demographic, water policies and regulations, attitude and practices on water resources factors were significant influencing the household water security. The factors statistically associated with household water security were socio demographic factors of gender of being female (adj. OR=0.40;0.23-0.69, P-value=0.001) and income level more than 350000 Tanzania shillings (adj. OR=7.18; 95% CI: 1.57-33.70, P-value=0.019), Time spent during wet seasons (adj. OR=4.22; 95% CI: 1.49-11.91, P-value=0.019), unprotected dug well water sources (adj. OR=15.41; 95% CI: 1.50-158.35, P-value=0.004) for water accessibility factors respectively.
