AU  - Williams, Emily
AU  - Funk, Chris
AU  - Shukla, Shraddhanand
AU  - McEvoy, Daniel
TI  - Quantifying human-induced temperature impacts on the 2018 United States four corners hydrologic and agro-pastoral drought.
T2  - Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society
M3  - Journal article
AB  - In this study, the potential temperature increase due to human-induced (HI) warming was estimated, and the impacts of elevated temperature (i) on vapour pressure deficit (VPD) using a statistical model, (ii) on agropastoral drought using a statistical model relating VPD and the Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI), and (iii) on hydrologic drought using a hydrologic model were subsequently examined. The study region encompasses the spatial extent of exceptional drought in WY2018 as defined by the USDM, covering large portions of New Mexico, Arizona, Utah, and Colorado, USA. WY2018 was exceptionally warm and dry, and an assessment of the Community Earth System Model version 1 (CESM1) and e Canadian Earth System Model version 2 (CanESM2) simulations suggested that HI warming increased air temperatures by ~1.3° to ~2°C, respectively. Relatively small changes in temperature can result in large changes in VPD; thus, if actual vapour pressure AVP remains constant, human-induced warming, alone, could explain ~60%-80% of the observed WY2018 VPDmaxanomalies. WY2018 experienced low NDVI values as reflected in the poor rangeland conditions reported by the USDM for much of New Mexico, Utah, and Arizona during the same period. HI increases in SVP values likely contributed to reduced August NDVI; the magnitude of greenup was smaller in actual 2018 NDVI compared to the counterfactuals. VIC simulations suggest that without the HI warming March SWE would have been ~24% (CanESM) or ~19% (CESM) higher and annual WY runoff would have been ~1.3% (CanESM) or ~1.43% (CESM) higher.
