AU  - Segnon, Alcade C.
AU  - Lamien, Nieyidouba
AU  - Zougmore, Robert B.
TI  - Climate-smart aquaculture and fisheries practices and technologies in West and Central Africa: a systematic review.
T2  - agriRxiv
M3  - Preprint
AB  - Climate change poses significant challenges to the sustainability of aquaculture and fisheries production in West and Central Africa, sectors that are critical for food security, nutrition, and livelihoods. Despite the region's rapid aquatic food production growth, overall production remains low compared to global levels, while capture fisheries remain dominant but highly vulnerable to climate variability. In this study, we conducted a systematic review of climate-smart aquaculture and fisheries (CSAF) technologies and practices in West and Central Africa, following the preferred reporting items for systematic reviews and meta-analyses (PRISMA) guidelines. From 359 publications retrieved, 90 studies, covering the period 2008-2023 met our inclusion criteria. Using a multi-criteria framework, aquaculture and fisheries technologies and practices identified were assessed for their contribution to the three pillars of climate-smart agriculture (CSA): productivity, adaptation, and mitigation. Results highlight recirculating aquaculture systems (RAS), Biofloc technology, water reuse and treatment systems, and integrated models such as aquaponics and integrated aquaculture-agriculture as the most promising climate-smart aquaculture practices. In fisheries, ecosystem-based fisheries management (EBFM) and protected areas management (PAMs) emerged as the climate-smart approaches. However, adoption remains uneven across countries, constrained by limited finance, weak institutional capacity, fragmented policies, and low access to extension services. This suggests that while technological solutions are essential, building resilient aquatic food systems in the region hinges on strategic public investments, effective risk reduction, and strengthened intergovernmental governance.
