AU  - Rossi, Jan Martin
TI  - Climate shocks and youth labour: gender-disaggregated evidence from sub-Saharan Africa.
T2  - Climate shocks and youth labour - gender-disaggregated evidence from sub-Saharan Africa
M3  - Miscellaneous
AB  - Sub-Saharan Africa (SSA) faces the dual challenge of expanding working opportunities for a rapidly growing youth population and safeguarding livelihoods from increasingly frequent extreme weather events. Despite the urgency of both issues, little evidence exists on how climate stressors affect the labour outcomes of young people in rural areas. To address this gap, we apply a double-hurdle regression model to a dataset combining socio-economic data with high-resolution climatic and geospatial information from rural areas in six SSA countries. Our results show that when rural areas are exposed to extreme heat, precipitation or droughts, young people adjust their engagement in productive labour in different ways than older adults. Moreover, these climate stressors contribute to a widening of gender gaps among youth. On the one hand, exposure to heat stress pushes young women out of productive labour, thereby widening the gap in participation between young women and young men. On the other hand, exposure to extreme precipitation and droughts is associated with a concentration of young female workers in the agricultural sector, and of young men in the non-agricultural sector. Our results highlight the importance of integrated labour and climate polices that are attentive to age and gender-specific challenges and opportunities.
