AU  - Ho, Ching-Hsien
TI  - The analysis of coastal fish species composition and abundance variations related to the marine environmental change in the Gongliao Village, Taiwan.
T2  - Journal of the Fisheries Society of Taiwan
M3  - Journal article
AB  - In addition to the impact of climate change on global marine environment and ecology, with the intensification of extreme climatic disasters, climate change and climate variability may pose greater harm and threats to regional or local fishery resources. Hence, it is of great necessity to lower the vulnerability of local fisheries and fisheries operators who largely depend on offshore fishery resources for making a living, by fighting against natural disasters and seeking to understand the impact and harm of climate change on coastal fisheries. In this study, we computed the Catch per Unit Effort (CPUE) of every fish species and selected the top 12 dominant fish species in coastal fisheries. An analysis of Multi-Dimensional Scaling (MDS) was carried out to detect significant differences among the catch compositions over a 16-year period. Finally, Principal Component Regression (PCR) analysis tested the relationships between environmental factors and each dominant fish species. The results based on the MDS and cluster analyses showed that the study period could be divided into two clusters (1996 - 2002, 2003 - 2012) with an 80% similarity value. The PCR analysis also showed that environmental factors with a CPUE of 10 species were significantly correlated (r2: 0.483 - 0.868;p< 0.05 orp< 0.01). This result highlights that environmental changes in the ocean are closely related to catch compositions in coastal fisheries. Changes in marine environment and ecology will increase the vulnerability of local fisheries and household fishery production, and affect the supply stability of the offshore fisheries. However, this issue not only plagues local fisheries in Taiwan, but also perplexes the offshore fishing villages of other countries. In particular, the climate impacts of the tropical and subtropical regions of the ocean are similar to those of Taiwan.
