AU  - Kolpin, D. W.
ED  - Williams, J. D.
ED  - Kolpin, D. W.
TI  - AWRA Spring Specialty Conference 'Agricultural Hydrology and Water Quality', Kansas City, Missouri, USA, May 2003.
T2  - Journal of the American Water Resources Association
M3  - Journal issue
M3  - Conference proceedings
AB  - This special issue contains 10 technical papers focusing on various topics in the area of agricultural hydrology and water quality, such as increased production of commercial fertilizers (nitrate and phosphorus), pesticides (e.g., imazamethabenz and glyphosate and herbicide transformation products) and their effects in associated water bodies, as well as animal feeding operations, concentrating formally to nonpoint sources of animal waste and veterinary pharmaceuticals. In addition, the origin and transport of dissolved chemicals in a karst watershed in Illinois (USA) are also covered. The capacity of native giant cane (Arundinaria gigantea) and hardwood riparian forest buffers to reduce orthophosphate or dissolved reactive phosphate are evaluated. Bioeconomic analysis of selected conservation practices on soil erosion and freshwater fisheries is also discussed. A hydrological modelling of the Iroquois river watershed using HSPF (Hydrological Simulation Program - FORTRAN) and SWAT (Soil and Water Assessment Tool) and a watershed scale modelling of critical source areas of runoff generation and phosphorus transport. Nine additional technical papers are also included in this issue. Topics covered in these papers are: curve number hydrology in water quality modelling; optimization method for calibrating tank model; summer low flows in New England during the 20th century; watershed based institutional approach to developing clean water resources; water column light attenuation in Danshuei river estuary in Taiwan; climate science and drought planning for Arizona; stable hydrogen and oxygen isotope composition of precipitation in northeastern Colorado; wave-induced flow and transport in sediment beds; and evaluation of HSPF in an arid, urbanized watershed.
