TI  - Preference of Satsuma mandarin grown by different managing methods.
T2  - Horticultural Research (Japan)
M3  - Journal article
AB  - A survey was conducted to determine preferences among Japanese consumers for satsuma mandarin (Citrus unshiu) grown under 3 crop management conditions (conventional management in an open field, and water stress types I and II, which consisted of water stress irrigation without creasing and with creasing, respectively). The respondents consisted of 127 males and 175 females (≥16 years old). For water stress types I and II, plants were grown in an open field covered with a water-permeable sheet. Fruits produced under water stress type II were the most preferred (64.5%), mainly due to the flavour and sugar to acid ratio of these fruits, followed by fruits produced under water stress type I (19.9%). Conventionally produced fruits were the least preferred (15.6%). The preference for fruits grown under water stress type II increased with the increase in the respondent's age, especially for the female respondents. The production systems markedly varied with regard to the reaction of the respondents to sweetness. However, in terms of sourness, the production systems did not significantly vary. With regard to fruit appearance, the respondents mostly preferred fruits grown under water stress type I and conventionally produced fruits. Water stress type II fruits were the most difficult to peel.
