TI  - Fertirrigation in graftedPinus pineaL. trees: denser crowns but no effect on cone production or masting cycles.
T2  - Forest Ecology and Management
M3  - Journal article
AB  - The high level of consumer awareness regarding healthy, nature-based and sustainable products, place kernels fromPinus pineaL. (stone pine) at the top of the list of non-wood forest products to be explored from an economic perspective in the Mediterranean basin. To meet this growing demand, efforts are being made to domesticate the species and increase its production potential. This study presents the results of a fertirrigation experiment carried out in a stone pine stand planted in 2010 and grafted at the age of 3. The experimental design comprises 2 blocks of 3 plots each established in a surface drip irrigation system with 3 treatments: a Control (C), a first level of fertirrigation (FR) and a second level of fertirrigation (2FR) which corresponds to the double of water and fertilization added to the first level. The fertirrigation treatment (FR) comprised a supplement of 41 mm (8%) of water to the natural hydrological year precipitation, on average, from 2014 to 2021, combined with an annual input of 100 kg ha-1of an NPK fertiliser (20 N:15P2O5:15K2O) added during the dry season (late spring to early autumn) in the irrigation system. The 2FR treatment received the double. Radial growth, shoot and needle elongation, needle nitrogen content, female strobili production and mortality and cone production (number and weight) were evaluated over 6 years. The number of female strobili per unit crown area did not vary between treatments in any year. However, growth variables indicated an improved physiological condition of the 2FR trees, especially during spring and summer, resulting in an overall 60% increase of female strobili that completed the ripening cycle compared to C trees. A 65% increase in the number of cones produced in the 2FR compared to the C was found, but this effect was only significant during one mast year and after a continuous five-year fertirrigation application. We observed that internal resources accumulation played a significant role in the masting habit of the species, ensuring the survival of female strobili even during a severe drought. Although the fertirrigation applied during the period of water scarcity did not allow a year-to-year regulation of cone production, the results highlight an opportunity to increase production potential by intensifying the use of water and fertilizers. Such investments should be carefully analysed from an economic standpoint, especially in Mediterranean countries where climate change is forcing a more responsible and sustainable use of water in the future.
