TI  - Transsexual forms of pistachio (Pistacia terebinthusL.) from Bulgaria - biotechnological approaches for preservation, multiplication and inclusion in selection programs.
T2  - Bulgarian Journal of Agricultural Science
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This paper discusses the application of biotechnological approaches to the multiplication and study of thePistacia(pistachio) - a nut fruit crop not widespread in Bulgaria, but whose economic significance in the Mediterranean region and other countries continues to increase. The main reasons for the expanding cultivation is the high nutritive value of the fruits, the existence of wild species, the potential for intergeneric and interspecies hybridization, and the exceptional drought resistance that allows its cultivation in non-irrigated soils prone to soil erosion. ThePistaciagenus includes 12 deciduous species, all of which are trees. These species are dioecious and anemophylic, and have their male and female flowers on separate trees. Among them, onlyP. verais domesticated. For the industrial plantations of pistachio, there should be a male tree for every 8-11 female trees, thus, 10% of the pistachio plantation is non-productive. In the summer of 2002, Dr. D. Avanzato found a rare transsexual form ofP. terebinthusin the Rhodopi Mountain. Later, the existence of a whole isolated population of these trees was determined. The trees are the first case of a defined transsexual form amongP. terebinthus. The application ofin vivoandin vitromethods for the propagation and molecular-marker-based genetic analysis of this transsexual form ofP. terebinthuswill allow its preservation, and use as a rootstock and donour for monoecy in pistachio hybridization programmes.
